english:
  title: On Cultivating the Plantain
  author: Kang Hee-maeng
  language: eng
  text: |-
    A certain magistrate of the capital, Lord Lee, sent his eldest son to seek instruction from the Cloud-Pine Hermit on how to grow and nurture plantains. The hermit asked, "How does your father tend them?" The son replied, "In winter we store them in clay vessels, yet they freeze; in spring we plant them in the courtyard, yet they will not flourish. This has happened more than once. How might we keep them unharmed through winter and unwithered through summer?" The hermit smiled and said, "Ah, between heaven and earth, countless are the grasses, trees, birds, beasts, and living things that depend upon proper nurture to thrive. Who can count how many creatures require such care? When care is lacking, the living grow still, the planted fall over, the flourishing wither, and all lose their essential nature. Why wonder at this? If all things require such tending, so too does the human heart. When seduced by fame and ambition, beset by hardship and disgrace, few can preserve their true nature intact. The plantain is the most delicate of all plants—too dry and it scorches, too wet and it rots. Follow the proper method and it thrives easily; neglect it and it withers just as easily. The secret of good cultivation lies in self-understanding. Go home and tell your father; he will nod knowingly and smile in silence." With this, he gave the roots and composed this discourse:

    The Creator scattered forth ten thousand things,
    Countless in their kinds,
    All cradled in Great Transformation,
    Harmonious and interpenetrating.
    Who maintains the hidden mechanism?
    Who ordains the myriad classes?
    Through Yang's bestowal and Yin's responsive change,
    Each finds its proper nature and destiny.

    When plants are severed from water and soil,
    They swiftly wilt and cease to flourish.

    There is a tender grass,
    Neither vine nor branch,
    Its leaves like gossamer silk,
    Its roots like crouching stone.
    By nature it fears the killing frost,
    Yet yearns for the nourishing dew.
    Though fragile in form,
    It lacks the steadfast bearing of pine and bamboo—
    Yet mark how, from its tender heart,
    Something precious emerges,
    Paralleling the dangerous yet subtle truth
    That dwells within human character.
    Fit indeed to plant it in the courtyard,
    Near the dwelling of the virtuous.

    How should one plant it?
    There is a proper method:
    When the earth's pulse awakens,
    When night brings no frost,
    Choose a place half-blessed by sun,
    Dig a wide circular pit,
    Set the roots and cover with soft, rich earth,
    Level it smooth with care,
    Water it constantly—let it never dry.
    Build a fence around to guard against harm.

    When spring's gentle warmth arrives,
    And southern breezes blow,
    The old stalks turn green,
    New leaves unfold in jade.
    Take fermented straw soaked in urine,
    Layer it deep around the plant.
    The sprouts drink in moisture and burst forth,
    The leaves swell with richness and vigor.
    Green tendrils rise like candle-flames,
    Blue fronds stretch like phoenix-tails,
    Delicate yet mighty, graceful yet strong,
    Outshading all common flowers.

    When summer stretches long in empty halls,
    And fine silk feels cool in the breeze,
    When incense from the precious censer curls,
    And the ancient melody concludes,
    When tangled feelings find no rest,
    And lonely sorrow grows oppressive—
    Suddenly the emerald leaves quiver and dance,
    As though silken tapestries were swaying.

    When autumn rains darken the bare courtyard,
    And behind the window few appear,
    When the blue lamp within flickers dimly,
    A thousand feelings rush upon the heart,
    And one longs to abandon the world and fly away—
    But hark! The sudden downpour sounds,
    Startling the melancholy spirit from its daze.

    When heaven clears and evening dew turns cold,
    When withered leaves break free in tattered streams,
    And fresh sprouts emerge in clustered rows,
    With a new knife prune the excess,
    Harvest the tender hearts by the basketful.
    Season them with all five flavors,
    Mix with pepper and ginger—
    That delicate yet subtle taste
    Surpasses even bear and lamb.

    When severe frost begins to bite,
    And all leaves have fallen,
    Command your servants to break open the earth,
    Leave a span of stalk, then cut it down,
    Store it in earthen vessels,
    Not in the center, but along the edges,
    Line the banks, mulch with dry chaff—
    Fear not the human breath,
    Warmth is what matters most.
    Shun cold and dampness,
    For they bring easy ruin.
    If you attend to the season and follow the method,
    Why should you fear its decline?

    When deep winter seals all with darkness and cold,
    Preserve one slender thread of Yang's warmth,
    Keep it gently, carefully sheltered—
    And lo, the sprouts emerge, the buds break forth!
    This steals transformation's work away,
    Leaking spring's light into winter's gloom.
    Transcending Yin and Yang, it endures alone,
    Growing ever more vigorous through all seasons.

    Yet mark—this is not true of plants alone.
    There is a secret method for human cultivation:
    Though material things have form and must pass away,
    All formed things must have their end—
    Yet Principle has no form, and shines eternal;
    The formless outlasts heaven and earth, endless.

    Then nurture and preserve it with your care,
    Examine it with steady scrutiny,
    But never force its growth.
    Respect the teachings of the sages,
    And cultivate yourself with diligence,
    That you might approach the path of the virtuous.
